DC\n| year        = 2007\n| isbn        = \n| asin        = \n| oclc        = \n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html\n| title       = The War of the Rebellion: A Compilation of the Official Records of the Union and Confederate Armies\n| author      = United States. War Department.\n| publisher   = U.S. Government Printing Office\n| location    = Washington, DC\n| year        = 1880-1901\n| isbn        = \n| asin        = \n| oclc        = \n| url-access  = \n}}{{PD-notice}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Illinois Civil War Units]]\n*[[Illinois in the American Civil War]]\n\n[[Category:Illinois Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-unit-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 98th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Infantry/Illinois Volunteer Mounted Infantry\n| image=Flag of Illinois.svg\n| image_size = 100\n|caption=Illinois flag\n|dates= September 3, 1862, to July 29, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Mounted infantry]]\n|equipment= [[Spencer repeating rifle]]\n| battles = [[American Civil War]]\n* [[Battle of Hoover's Gap]]\n* [[Battle of Chickamauga]]\n* [[Battle of Resaca]]\n* [[Siege of Atlanta]]\n}}\nThe '''98th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Infantry''', later the '''98th Regiment Illinois Volunteer Mounted Infantry''', was an [[infantry]] and [[mounted infantry]] [[regiment]] that served in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]<ref name=\"Dyer\">Dyer</ref>.\n\n==Service==\nThe 98th Illinois Infantry was organized at [[Centralia, Illinois]] and mustered into Federal service on September 3, 1862<ref name=\"OoB\">Official Records of the American Civil War of the Union and Confederate Armies, U.S. War Department</ref><ref>Baumgartner, p. 70</ref>.\n\nThe regiment was converted to mounted infantry on March 8, 1863<ref name=\"Repeaters\">Wilder's Lightning Brigade and Its Spencer Repeaters, Sunderland</ref>\n. An element of \"Wilder's [[Lightning Brigade (US Army of the Cumberland 1863)|Lightning Brigade]]\", a unit that pioneered the use of [[mounted infantry]].<ref name=\"Lightning\">Lightning at Hoover's Gap: the Story of Wilder's Brigade, Sunderland</ref> As part of that brigade, it performed admirably in the Tullahoma<ref name=\"Lightning\" /><ref name=\"Kennedy225\">Kennedy, p. 225.</ref> and Chickamauga campaigns. Its superior firepower<ref name=\"Repeaters\">Wilder's Lightning Brigade and Its Spencer Repeaters, Sunderland</ref> due to its Spencers was found to allow it to take on an enemy that outnumbered them on several occasions and triumph.\n\nThe regiment was mustered out on June 27, 1865, and discharged at [[Springfield, Illinois]], on July 7, 1865<ref name=\"OoB\">Official Records of the American Civil War of the Union and Confederate Armies, U.S. War Department</ref>.\n\n==Total strength and casualties==\nThe regiment suffered 30 enlisted men who were killed in action or who died of their wounds and 5 officers and 136 enlisted men who died of disease, for a total of 171 fatalities.<ref name=\"Dyer\" />\n\n==Commanders==\n*Colonel John J. Funkhouser - Discharged due to wounds July 5, 1864.<ref>http://www.rootsweb.com/~ilcivilw/f&s/098-fs.htm Illinois in the Cvil war website after Illinois Adjutant General's muster rolls</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/blue-lightning-wilders-mounted-infantry-brigade-in-the-battle-of-chickamauga/oclc/232639520?loc=02333\n| title       = Blue Lightning: Wilder's Mounted Brigade in the Battle of Chickamauga\n| author      = Baumgartner, Richard A.\n| publisher   = Blue Acorn Press\n| locat